04198nam a22006495i 9780824861322DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t19971997hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248613227 a10.1515/97808248613222doi  a(DE-B1597)550596  a(OCoLC)1312726821  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aPL788.4.G43bB37 1997eb 7aLIT0080002bisacsh04a895.6/312201 aBargen, Doris G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Woman's Weapon :bSpirit Possession in The Tale of Genji /cDoris G. Bargen. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[1997] 4cÂ©1997  a1 online resource (420 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tEmblems -- tIntroduction -- tEnter mono no ke: Spirit Possession in Cultural Context -- tExit mono no ke: Spirit Possession in The Tale of Genji -- tAppendix A: Genji Chronology -- tAppendix B: Genealogical Charts -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this subtle and highly original reading of Murasaki Shikibu's 11th-century classic The Tale of Genji (Genji monogatari), Bargen explores the role of possessing spirits (mono no ke) from a female viewpoint. In several key episodes of the Genji, Heian noblewomen (or their mediums) tremble, speak in strange voices, and tear their hair and clothing while under the spell of mono no ke. For literary critics, Genji, the male protagonist, is central to determining the role of these spirits. From this male-centered perspective, female jealousy provides a convenient explanation for the emergence of mono no ke within the polygynous marital system of the Heian aristocracy. Yet this conventional view fails to take into account the work's female authorship and its largely female audience. Relying upon anthropological as well as literary evidence, Doris G. Bargen foregrounds the motives of the possessed character and locates mono no ke within the politics of Heian society, interpreting spirit possession as a female strategy adopted to counter male strategies of empowerment. Possessions become "performances" by women attempting to redress the balance of power; they subtly subvert the structure of domination and significantly alter the construction of gender.A Woman's Weapon will find an appreciative audience not only among Genji specialists but also among scholars in the fields of anthropology and gender studies who are curious about the complex phenomenon of spirit possession as reflected in the mirror of a major literary work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aSpirit possession in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311056415040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486132240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824861322423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824861322/original  a978-3-11-056415-0  University of Hawaii Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK